"What is the particle model of matter?","A model that explains solids, liquids and gases as particles with different spacing and movement.","Particle model"
"What are the states of matter?","Solid, liquid, gas.","Particle model"
"What happens to particles when a solid melts?","They gain energy, vibrate more, and can move past each other.","Particle model"
"What is density?","Mass per unit volume.","Particle model"
"What is the density equation?","density = mass ÷ volume (ρ = m/V).","Particle model"
"How do you calculate mass from density and volume?","mass = density × volume (m = ρV).","Particle model"
"What is internal energy?","The total kinetic and potential energy of particles in a substance.","Particle model"
"What is temperature (particle model)?","A measure of the average kinetic energy of particles.","Particle model"
"What is specific heat capacity?","Energy needed to raise 1 kg of a substance by 1°C.","Particle model"
"What is the specific heat capacity equation?","energy = mass × specific heat capacity × temperature change (E = mcΔT).","Particle model"
"What is specific latent heat?","Energy needed to change state of 1 kg without changing temperature.","Particle model"
"What is the specific latent heat equation?","energy = mass × specific latent heat (E = mL).","Particle model"
"What does a heating curve show?","How temperature changes as energy is added, including plateaus at state changes.","Particle model"
"What is evaporation?","Liquid particles escaping from the surface to become gas.","Particle model"
"What is condensation?","Gas particles losing energy and becoming liquid.","Particle model"
"What is sublimation?","Solid changing directly to gas.","Particle model"
"What is a mixture?","Two or more substances not chemically combined.","Particle model"
"What is a pure substance?","Only one element or one compound.","Particle model"
"What is pressure in a gas?","Force from gas particles colliding with container walls.","Particle model"
"What happens to gas pressure if temperature increases (fixed volume)?","Pressure increases because particles move faster and collide more often.","Particle model"
"What is the unit of pressure?","Pascals (Pa).","Particle model"
"What is the difference between mass and weight?","Mass is amount of matter (kg); weight is force due to gravity (N).","Forces"
"What is weight?","The gravitational force on an object.","Forces"
"What is the weight equation?","weight = mass × gravitational field strength (W = mg).","Forces"
"What is gravitational field strength on Earth?","About 9.8 N/kg (often taken as 10 N/kg).","Forces"
"What is a contact force?","A force that acts when objects touch (e.g., friction, normal contact).","Forces"
"What is a non-contact force?","A force that acts at a distance (e.g., gravity, magnetism, electrostatic).","Forces"
"What is friction?","A force that opposes motion between surfaces in contact.","Forces"
"What is air resistance (drag)?","A frictional force from air that opposes motion.","Forces"
"What is the normal contact force?","The support force from a surface on an object.","Forces"
"What is a resultant force?","The overall force after adding all forces acting on an object.","Forces"
"What happens if the resultant force is zero?","The object is at rest or moving at constant velocity.","Forces"
"What is Newton’s First Law?","If resultant force is zero, an object stays at rest or moves at constant velocity.","Forces"
"What is Newton’s Second Law?","Force causes acceleration: F = ma.","Forces"
"What is Newton’s Third Law?","For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.","Forces"
"What is the equation linking force, mass and acceleration?","F = ma.","Forces"
"What are the units of force?","Newtons (N).","Forces"
